# Skills Library — Windsurf security rules
# Auto-generated by skills-check. Do not edit by hand.

Apply every rule below to every change in this workspace.

[HIGH] API Security
  ALWAYS - Require authentication on every non-public endpoint. Default to authenticated; opt out for genuinely public routes by explicit annotation.
  ALWAYS - Apply authorization at the object level — confirm the authenticated subject actually has access to the requested resource ID, not just that they're logged in (defeats the OWASP API1 BOLA / IDOR class).
  ALWAYS - Validate all request inputs against an explicit schema (JSON Schema, Pydantic, Zod, validator/v10 struct tags). Reject early; never propagate untrusted input deeper.
  ALWAYS - Enforce rate limits at the route level for authentication endpoints, password reset, and any expensive operation.
  ALWAYS - Use short-lived access tokens (≤ 1 hour) with refresh tokens, not long-lived bearer tokens.
  ALWAYS - Return generic error messages externally (`invalid credentials`) and log specifics internally — avoid leaking which of username/password was wrong.
  ALWAYS - Include `Cache-Control: no-store` on responses containing personal or sensitive data.
  NEVER  - Use sequential integer IDs in URLs for resources accessible across tenants. Use UUIDs or unguessable opaque IDs.
  NEVER  - Trust `Authorization` headers without verifying the signature and expiration.
  NEVER  - Accept `none` algorithm JWTs. Pin the expected algorithm at verification time.
  NEVER  - Mass-assign request bodies directly to ORM models (`User(**request.json)`) — this enables privilege escalation when the model has admin fields the user shouldn't control.
  NEVER  - Disable CSRF protection on state-changing endpoints used by browsers.
  NEVER  - Return stack traces or framework error pages to the client in production.
  NEVER  - Use `HTTP GET` for any state-changing operation — GET should be safe and idempotent.
  OK     - Public marketing-site endpoints serving anonymous traffic legitimately have no auth and no rate limits beyond the load balancer.
  OK     - Sequential IDs in paths are fine for genuinely public, non-tenant-scoped resources (e.g. blog post slugs, public product catalog items).
  OK     - Health-check endpoints (`/healthz`, `/ready`) intentionally bypass auth.

[MEDIUM] Compliance Awareness
  ALWAYS - Tag functions that handle PII / PHI / PCI data with a comment indicating the classification (e.g. `// classification: PII`).
  ALWAYS - Log audit events for security-relevant actions (login, permission change, data export, admin operations) — log who, what, when, NOT the sensitive payload.
  ALWAYS - Identify the CWE / OWASP category for security-relevant code in comments when the team's convention is to include traceability (`// addresses CWE-79 — XSS`).
  ALWAYS - For PCI scope, segregate card-data-handling code into clearly-named modules so scope boundaries are visible.
  ALWAYS - For HIPAA workloads, prefer encryption at rest AND in transit, with documented key management.
  NEVER  - Include PII / PHI / PCI in log messages, error messages, or telemetry events.
  NEVER  - Store payment card numbers, CVVs, or full magnetic stripe data outside of a PCI DSS-compliant tokenization service.
  NEVER  - Mix PII-handling code into general utility modules without explicit classification.
  NEVER  - Generate code that processes EU residents' personal data without considering GDPR obligations (right to erasure, data minimization, lawful basis).
  NEVER  - Suggest workarounds that bypass compliance controls "for development" — these workarounds always leak into production.
  OK     - Logs of *types* of data accessed ("user accessed claim record") are usually fine; the rule is against logging the *contents* of sensitive fields.
  OK     - Test fixtures using clearly fake data (`555-0100` phone numbers, `4111-1111-1111-1111` PAN, `John Doe`) are not PII.
  OK     - Audit log retention is intentionally long (often years) and should not be filtered by general data-retention sweeps.

[HIGH] Dependency Audit
  ALWAYS - Pin dependencies to exact versions in lockfiles (`package-lock.json`, `yarn.lock`, `Pipfile.lock`, `poetry.lock`, `go.sum`, `Cargo.lock`).
  ALWAYS - Cross-check every new dependency name against the bundled malicious-package list in `vulnerabilities/supply-chain/malicious-packages/`.
  ALWAYS - Prefer well-established packages with high download counts, multiple maintainers, and recent activity over newer alternatives that solve the same problem.
  ALWAYS - Run the package manager's audit command (`npm audit`, `pip-audit`, `cargo audit`, `govulncheck`) and review reported issues before merging.
  ALWAYS - Verify the package's repository URL on the package page actually exists and matches the linked GitHub / GitLab / Codeberg project.
  NEVER  - Add a dependency without pinning its version.
  NEVER  - Install packages with `--unsafe-perm` or equivalent flags that bypass install sandboxing.
  NEVER  - Add a dependency whose name appears in the bundled malicious-package list.
  NEVER  - Add a brand-new package (published within the last 30 days) without a clear, documented reason — typosquats are usually freshly published.
  NEVER  - Use the `latest` tag in a production lockfile or container image FROM line.
  NEVER  - Commit unused dependencies — they expand the attack surface for free.
  OK     - Internal monorepo packages (`@yourco/*`) flagged as "unknown" — these are valid when the namespace is owned by your organization.
  OK     - New patch versions of stable packages (e.g. `react@18.2.5` after `18.2.4`) flagged as "recently published" — patch updates are usually fine.
  OK     - Package names that legitimately overlap with malicious entries from years ago that have been re-registered by the original maintainer.

[HIGH] Infrastructure Security
  ALWAYS - Pin base images by digest (`FROM image@sha256:...`) when building containers for production. Tags are mutable; digests are not.
  ALWAYS - Run containers as a non-root `USER` other than `0`. Add `securityContext: runAsNonRoot: true` to K8s pod specs.
  ALWAYS - Set explicit Kubernetes resource requests AND limits (`requests.cpu`, `requests.memory`, `limits.cpu`, `limits.memory`).
  ALWAYS - Drop all Linux capabilities and re-add only what's required (`securityContext.capabilities.drop: ["ALL"]`).
  ALWAYS - Mark filesystems read-only (`securityContext.readOnlyRootFilesystem: true`) when the workload doesn't legitimately need write access.
  ALWAYS - Enable encryption at rest (`enable_kms_encryption`, `kms_key_id`, `server_side_encryption_configuration`) for S3 buckets, EBS volumes, RDS, DynamoDB.
  ALWAYS - Set `block_public_access` on every S3 bucket unless the workload genuinely serves public content.
  ALWAYS - Apply the principle of least privilege to IAM policies: name explicit actions and resources; avoid `*:*` and `Resource: "*"` outside of intentional admin policies.
  NEVER  - Use `latest` as the image tag in production manifests.
  NEVER  - Run a container with `--privileged` flag or `securityContext.privileged: true`.
  NEVER  - Mount the host `/var/run/docker.sock` into a container.
  NEVER  - Expose Kubernetes services with `type: LoadBalancer` on the open internet without an ingress controller, WAF, or authentication layer in front.
  NEVER  - Hardcode AWS keys / GCP service-account keys / Azure client secrets in IaC. Use IRSA, GKE Workload Identity, Azure managed identities, or the platform-native equivalent.
  NEVER  - Create S3 buckets with `acl = "public-read"` for buckets containing anything other than intentionally public assets.
  NEVER  - Allow `0.0.0.0/0` ingress on database, SSH, RDP, or admin ports.
  NEVER  - Disable `node_to_node_encryption` on Elasticsearch / OpenSearch.
  OK     - Pinning image digests is not always practical in dev / preview environments — tag pinning (e.g. `node:20.11.1-alpine`) is acceptable there.
  OK     - `Resource: "*"` is acceptable in policies that are documented admin-only with explicit `Condition` constraints.
  OK     - `runAsNonRoot: false` is acceptable when the workload genuinely requires root (e.g., binding to port 80, certain network tooling). Document why.

[CRITICAL] Secret Detection
  ALWAYS - Check all string literals longer than 20 characters near keywords: `api_key`, `secret`, `token`, `password`, `credential`, `auth`, `bearer`, `private_key`, `access_key`, `client_secret`, `refresh_token`.
  ALWAYS - Flag any string matching known secret patterns: `AKIA[0-9A-Z]{16}` (AWS access key), `ghp_[A-Za-z0-9_]{36}` (GitHub PAT), `gho_[A-Za-z0-9_]{36}` (GitHub OAuth), `sk-[A-Za-z0-9]{48}` (OpenAI), `xox[baprs]-[A-Za-z0-9-]+` (Slack), `-----BEGIN.*PRIVATE KEY-----` (PEM private key).
  ALWAYS - Verify `.gitignore` includes: `*.pem`, `*.key`, `.env`, `.env.*`, `*credentials*`, `*secret*`, `id_rsa*`, `*.ppk`.
  ALWAYS - Prefer environment variable usage (`os.environ`, `process.env`, `os.Getenv`) over hardcoded values for any credential, connection string, or API endpoint that has an attached secret.
  ALWAYS - Suggest a secret manager (1Password, AWS Secrets Manager, HashiCorp Vault, Doppler) when credentials must be shared across machines or services.
  NEVER  - Commit files matching: `*.pem`, `*.key`, `*.p12`, `*.pfx`, `.env`, `.env.local`, `*credentials*`, `id_rsa`, `id_dsa`, `id_ecdsa`, `id_ed25519`.
  NEVER  - Hardcode API keys, tokens, passwords, or connection strings in source code.
  NEVER  - Include real secrets in test fixtures — use documented placeholders such as `AKIAIOSFODNN7EXAMPLE`, `wJalrXUtnFEMI/K7MDENG/bPxRfiCYEXAMPLEKEY`, or `xoxb-EXAMPLE-EXAMPLE`.
  NEVER  - Log or print secret values, even in debug mode.
  NEVER  - Echo secrets to terminals in CI logs (mask via `::add-mask::` in GitHub Actions).
  NEVER  - Embed signing keys in container images, even base images.
  OK     - AWS documentation example: `AKIAIOSFODNN7EXAMPLE` and the matching secret access key `wJalrXUtnFEMI/K7MDENG/bPxRfiCYEXAMPLEKEY`.
  OK     - Strings containing: "example", "test", "placeholder", "dummy", "sample", "changeme", "your-key-here", "REPLACE_ME", "TODO", "FIXME", "XXX".
  OK     - Hash literals in CSS/SCSS (e.g., `#ff0000`, `#deadbeef`).
  OK     - Base64-encoded non-secret content in tests (lorem ipsum encoded, image fixtures).
  OK     - Git commit SHAs in changelogs and release notes.
  OK     - JWT tokens in the OAuth RFC documentation examples (`eyJ...` strings appearing in comments).

[HIGH] Secure Code Review
  ALWAYS - Use parameterized queries / prepared statements for all database access. Never build SQL by string concatenation, even for "trusted" inputs.
  ALWAYS - Validate input at the trust boundary — type, length, allowed characters, allowed range — and reject before processing.
  ALWAYS - Encode output for the rendering context (HTML escape for HTML, URL encode for query params, JSON encode for JSON output).
  ALWAYS - Use the language's built-in cryptography library, never custom-rolled crypto. Prefer AES-GCM for symmetric encryption, Ed25519 / RSA-PSS for signatures, Argon2id / bcrypt for password hashing.
  ALWAYS - Use `crypto/rand` (Go), `secrets` module (Python), `crypto.randomBytes` (Node.js), or the platform CSPRNG for any random value involved in security (tokens, IDs, session keys).
  ALWAYS - Set explicit security headers on HTTP responses: `Content-Security-Policy`, `Strict-Transport-Security`, `X-Content-Type-Options: nosniff`, `Referrer-Policy`.
  ALWAYS - Use the principle of least privilege for file paths, database users, IAM policies, and process privileges.
  NEVER  - Build SQL/NoSQL queries by string concatenation with user input.
  NEVER  - Pass user input directly to `exec`, `system`, `eval`, `Function()`, `child_process`, `subprocess.run(shell=True)`, or any other command-execution path.
  NEVER  - Trust client-side validation. Always re-validate server-side.
  NEVER  - Use `MD5` or `SHA1` for any new security-sensitive purpose (passwords, signatures, HMAC). Use SHA-256 / SHA-3 / BLAKE2 / Argon2id instead.
  NEVER  - Use ECB mode for any encryption, ever. Prefer GCM, CCM, or ChaCha20-Poly1305.
  NEVER  - Use `==` for password comparison — use a constant-time comparison (`hmac.compare_digest`, `crypto.timingSafeEqual`, `subtle.ConstantTimeCompare`).
  NEVER  - Allow user input to determine file paths without canonicalization and allowlist checks (defends against `../../../etc/passwd` style path traversal).
  NEVER  - Disable TLS certificate verification in production code — `verify=False`, `InsecureSkipVerify: true`, `rejectUnauthorized: false`.
  OK     - Internal admin tools intentionally executing shell commands against trusted, fixed arguments are acceptable when documented and code-reviewed.
  OK     - Cryptographic test vectors using `MD5` / `SHA1` for compatibility with documented protocols (e.g. legacy interop tests) are acceptable.
  OK     - Constant-time comparison is overkill for non-secret comparisons (string equality in logs, tag matching).

[CRITICAL] Supply Chain Security
  ALWAYS - Compute Levenshtein distance against the top-1000 list for the relevant ecosystem whenever proposing a new dependency. Flag any candidate with distance ≤ 2 from a popular package (`axois` vs `axios`, `urlib3` vs `urllib3`, `colours` vs `colors`, `python-dateutil` vs `dateutil` vs `dateutils`).
  ALWAYS - Verify that internal-namespace packages (`@yourco/*`, `com.yourco.*`) are pulled from the internal registry, not the public one. Configure `.npmrc` / `pip.conf` / `settings.gradle` with the internal scope explicitly.
  ALWAYS - Pin the registry URL in lockfiles to prevent registry redirection attacks.
  ALWAYS - Check that any newly added package has a verified maintainer (`npm` provenance, `sigstore` signature, or GPG-signed git tag) when published in the last 90 days.
  ALWAYS - Treat install scripts (`postinstall`, `preinstall`, `setup.py` arbitrary code, `build.rs`) as high-risk surface and flag them in the PR description for human review.
  NEVER  - Add a public package whose name matches an internal namespace pattern.
  NEVER  - Trust a package whose repository URL on the registry page does not match its actual source repo.
  NEVER  - Recommend a freshly-published package with low download counts for a security-critical use case (auth, crypto, HTTP, DB drivers).
  NEVER  - Disable the package manager's integrity check (`--no-package-lock`, `--ignore-scripts = false` when defending against it, `npm config set audit false` in production).
  NEVER  - Auto-merge dependency-bump PRs without a reviewer when the bump crosses a major version.
  NEVER  - Suggest installing tools via `curl | sh` patterns from untrusted sources.
  OK     - Legitimate orgs forking and republishing maintained packages with a `-fork` or `-community` suffix; verify the fork's repo URL before flagging.
  OK     - Beta / alpha releases of well-known packages (e.g. `next@canary`) appear "newly published" but are part of a known release cadence.
  OK     - Internal namespace packages (`@yourco/internal-tools`) intentionally not on the public registry — these are fine when the `.npmrc` is configured correctly.

